I understand where people are coming from when they talk about comparing themselves on social media. But it's not something people can blame social media for. People can feel the same way doing their weekly food shop but they don't say "Aw Aldi made me feel *insert negative emotion here*". Social media is an inanimate platform where people are posting whatever really, and peoples response to that is up to them. (setting targeted harassment & bullying etc aside, they're different topics entirely) If people find that to be negative then there's self awareness work to be done within themselves to identify why they feel like that and how they can improve it that goes beyond pointing to an app and saying it's your fault. From a Mental Health perspective and human psychology, people don't like to admit they can do something better. They don't like to admit when there's something they're doing that's detrimental to themselves. It's easier to be able to say something or someone is the cause because we can compartmentalise that better. It's one of the reasons that some mental health conditions can be so difficult to understand for example because often there are no identifiable causes, the emotions are just there and we can't point to something that's the soul cause. So overall if we were to use a technique called The RP (responsibility pie - its a CBT technique for rationalising emotional responses) the percentage of responsibility you would assign to social media for how you feel would be very very low in comparison the the percentage you asign to yourself. People often reject this idea but if you think about it it's a hugely positive thing ⭐ If social media was the soul cause for your thought patterns we'd be throwing up our hands saying we have no say or control. But when we acknowledge our own part played by our own thinking we realise just how much control we have and how much of an ability we have to improve it 👌🏼

Very long rambles I know, but Mental Health topics are never cut and dry and I think to dash out a few words in summary would've done a disservice 🙈

not specific to social media but i was doing an art course and i loved it, we then went into lockdown in march and it was still fine, we were just doing it over zoom, but as soon as we were allowed back into the classroom everything changed SO much. i was constantly comparing myself to other people and the art they were creating, which i'd never done before lockdown (this was my third year in the course). it got the point i'd feel so anxious being in the classroom because i'd convinced myself everything everyone else was doing would be so much better than mine, i didn't even want to try because i didn't see the point. once i got home i cried, and i knew i had to withdraw from the course. i feel so much better now that i've left. a little bit of comparison is okay, i think, as long as it motivates you to try harder/new things, but if you feel so deflated and upset (like i did) it's best to let it go.
